<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Germany">Germany</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Burgher_arms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Germany"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Although assumption of arms always remained free, the emperors of the <a href="/wiki/Holy_Roman_Empire" title="Holy Roman Empire">Holy Roman Empire</a> since <a href="/wiki/Charles_IV,_Holy_Roman_Emperor" title="Charles IV, Holy Roman Emperor">Charles IV</a> began to grant arms without raising people to nobiliary status. In the 15th century the authority to grant arms was delegated to “<a href="/wiki/Hofpfalzgraf" class="mw-redirect" title="Hofpfalzgraf">Counts Palatine of the Imperial Court</a>” (<a href="/wiki/German_language" title="German language">German</a>: <i lang="de"><a href="https://de.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hofpfalzgraf" class="extiw" title="de:Hofpfalzgraf">Hofpfalzgrafen</a></i>), who from then on also granted arms to burghers. This was regarded as luxury everyone was not able to afford.
</p><p>The <a href="/w/index.php?title=Tilting_helmet&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Tilting helmet (page does not exist)">tilting helmet</a> was prescribed for arms of non-nobles, while the barred helmet was restricted by the imperial chancellery to the nobility as upholders of the tradition of tourneying. This privilege was also shared by certain people who enjoyed the same standing as the nobility, e.g. those who had a doctor's title in law or theology.<sup id="cite_ref-8" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>
Custom of the use of the barred helmet was also followed by city <a href="/wiki/Patricianship" class="mw-redirect" title="Patricianship">patricians</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-Heraldik_1998_p._173_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Heraldik_1998_p._173-9">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> Although the rule of the use of the tilting helmet by burghers was not always obeyed, it has still become the norm in many countries of the <a href="/wiki/Heraldry#German-Nordic_heraldry" title="Heraldry">German-Nordic heraldic tradition</a>, e.g. in <a href="/wiki/Swedish_heraldry" title="Swedish heraldry">Swedish heraldry</a>.
</p><p>After the fall of the <a href="/wiki/Holy_Roman_Empire" title="Holy Roman Empire">Holy Roman Empire</a>, arms were no longer granted to burghers except in the <a href="/wiki/Kingdom_of_Saxony" title="Kingdom of Saxony">Kingdom of Saxony</a>, where such grants continued from 1911 until 1918.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (August 2013)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup> Elsewhere burgher arms were assumed. Such family heraldry is still alive in Germany and burgher arms <a href="/wiki/Law_of_arms" class="mw-redirect" title="Law of arms">are protected by law</a>.
</p>
<p><b>Examples of German burgher arms:</b></p><ul class="gallery mw-gallery-traditional">
		<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 155px">
			<div class="thumb" style="width: 150px; height: 150px;"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Duerer.JPG" class="mw-file-description" title="Canting arms of the German painter Albrecht Dürer (1471–1528)"><img alt="Canting arms of the German painter Albrecht Dürer (1471–1528)" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2d/Duerer.JPG/95px-Duerer.JPG" decoding="async" width="95" height="120" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2d/Duerer.JPG/143px-Duerer.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2d/Duerer.JPG/191px-Duerer.JPG 2x" data-file-width="2451" data-file-height="3079" /></a></span></div>
			<div class="gallerytext"><a href="/wiki/Canting_arms" title="Canting arms">Canting arms</a> of the German painter <a href="/wiki/Albrecht_D%C3%BCrer" title="Albrecht Dürer">Albrecht Dürer</a> (1471–1528)</div>
		</li>
		<li class="gallerybox" style="width: 155px">
			<div class="thumb" style="width: 150px; height: 150px;"><span typeof="mw:File"><a href="/wiki/File:Albrecht_D%C3%BCrer_038.jpg" class="mw-file-description" title="Arms of Jakob Heller from the Heller Altarpiece by Albrecht Dürer"><img alt="Arms of Jakob Heller from the Heller Altarpiece by Albrecht Dürer" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/Albrecht_D%C3%BCrer_038.jpg/120px-Albrecht_D%C3%BCrer_038.jpg" decoding="async" width="120" height="112" class="mw-file-element" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/Albrecht_D%C3%BCrer_038.jpg/180px-Albrecht_D%C3%BCrer_038.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a5/Albrecht_D%C3%BCrer_038.jpg/240px-Albrecht_D%C3%BCrer_038.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2400" data-file-height="2239" /></a></span></div>
			<div class="gallerytext">Arms of <a href="/wiki/Jakob_Heller" title="Jakob Heller">Jakob Heller</a> from the <i><a href="/wiki/Heller_Altarpiece" title="Heller Altarpiece">Heller Altarpiece</a></i> by <a href="/wiki/Albrecht_D%C3%BCrer" title="Albrecht Dürer">Albrecht Dürer</a></div>
		</li>
</ul>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Portugal">Portugal</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Burgher_arms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Portugal"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>
<p>Burgher arms had a complicated and suppressed history in Portugal. During the reign of King <a href="/wiki/Afonso_V_of_Portugal" title="Afonso V of Portugal">Afonso V</a>, burgher arms were restricted to the use of colours only. This restriction would become irrelevant when King <a href="/wiki/Manuel_I_of_Portugal" title="Manuel I of Portugal">Manuel I</a> forbade the use of arms to those who were not of the <a href="/wiki/Portuguese_nobility" title="Portuguese nobility">Portuguese nobility</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> This restriction against burgher arms in Portugal lasted until the establishment of the Republic in 1910.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Arms_of_peasants">Arms of peasants</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Burgher_arms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Arms of peasants"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>In some regions (<a href="/wiki/Normandy" title="Normandy">Normandy</a>, <a href="/wiki/County_of_Flanders" title="County of Flanders">Flanders</a>) even peasants sometimes bore arms.<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup>
In <a href="/wiki/Switzerland" title="Switzerland">Switzerland</a> 14th century arms of farmers are known, but they are rare and did not become numerous until the 17th century,<sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> as well as in <a href="/wiki/Lower_Saxony" title="Lower Saxony">Lower Saxony</a>, <a href="/wiki/Frisia" title="Frisia">Frisia</a> and <a href="/wiki/County_of_Tyrol" title="County of Tyrol">Tyrol</a>, where farmers had personal freedom.<sup id="cite_ref-Heraldik_1998_p._173_9-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Heraldik_1998_p._173-9">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> In <a href="/wiki/Denmark" title="Denmark">Denmark</a> arms of farmers are preserved on seals from about 1300.<sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> In <a href="/wiki/Norway" title="Norway">Norway</a> peasants have used arms since the Middle Ages and some of the arms have even been used as family arms.<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="See_also">See also</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=Burgher_arms&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: See also"><span>edit</span></a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
